  "target_response": {
    "text": "You can absolutely still run tomorrow — an easy one is actually the best medicine here. Post-leg-day soreness typically peaks around 24 to 48 hours after the session and fades across the following day or two, so tomorrow may honestly feel worse before it feels better; that's the normal arc, not a setback. Gentle movement helps it along: an easy, flat run at conversational pace boosts blood flow without adding much new damage, and most people find the legs loosen up after the first ten minutes or so. What tomorrow shouldn't be is intervals or hills. The line to respect is pain quality — a dull, both-sides ache in the muscles is soreness; anything sharp, one-sided, or centred on a joint means stop and reassess. What you're describing sounds firmly like the first kind.",
